{{- /*
facts-gate.sh.tmpl — THE bash implementation of the gate-expression grammar
(KTD6), shared by every consumer that gates something on a named host fact:

  <fact>          boolean fact is true       nvidia, thinkpad, gdm
  !<fact>         boolean fact is false      !virt   (bareMetalPackages)
  <fact>.<value>  string fact equals value   desktop.kde, desktop.gnome

Emits ONE bash function, `fact_gate()`, that evaluates a gate expression
against the FACT_* variables .chezmoitemplates/facts-sh.tmpl already assigned
in the calling script (boolean facts as `1`/`0`, string facts as a bare word —
facts-sh.tmpl's convention, NOT the raw `true`/`false` facts.tmpl itself
emits), and returns 0 (gate holds) or 1 (it does not) — a plain predicate:

  {{ includeTemplate "facts-sh.tmpl" . }}
  {{ includeTemplate "facts-gate.sh.tmpl" . }}

  HAS_NVIDIA=0; fact_gate "nvidia" && HAS_NVIDIA=1
  if fact_gate "vm"; then …

Call it AFTER facts-sh.tmpl in every consuming script — fact_gate() reads the
FACT_* variables, it does not assign them.

Argument: the root chezmoi context, exactly like facts-sh.tmpl (NOT a dict —
this partial needs nothing else, so it does not take the "ctx"/"name" dict
shape .chezmoitemplates/headless-guard.sh.tmpl and its siblings do).

WHY THIS IS THE ONE IMPLEMENTATION, NOT A THIRD (OR FOURTH) COPY OF THE SAME
THREE LINES: before this partial existed, the grammar was hand-written twice
more, and one caller did not evaluate it at all —
  * install-system-10-files' gate_ok() was a `case` ladder, one hand-written
    arm per fact NAME actually used as a system.yaml `gate:` — correct, but a
    new gated fact meant a new arm to remember to add.
  * dot_local/bin/host-facts' private gate_eval() was already generic, but it
    resolved a gate against ITS OWN report array (built straight from
    facts.tmpl's raw `true`/`false`), not the FACT_* variables the installers
    actually branch on — two readings of one registry that could quietly
    drift apart.
  * The two package installers did not evaluate a gate EXPRESSION at all: each
    HAS_ / IS_ flag was hand-seeded straight from a FACT_* variable named in
    the installer's own prose, and packages.yaml's `gates:` map was read only
    far enough to validate it, never to DRIVE anything. Editing a `gates:`
    value therefore changed nothing at runtime — see the former "declaration,
    not a switch" header in .chezmoidata/packages.yaml, rewritten now that
    this partial makes the map load-bearing.
  All four call sites now go through fact_gate() instead.

WHAT THIS PARTIAL DELIBERATELY DOES NOT DO:

  * VALIDATE. facts-validate.tmpl already fails the whole chezmoi command at
    RENDER time on a malformed expression — an unknown fact, a boolean
    compared to a value, a negated dotted form, a `desktop.<typo>` outside the
    fact's declared `values:` — and every caller of fact_gate() below already
    runs its gate expressions through facts-validate.tmpl BEFORE any of them
    ever reaches a `fact_gate "…"` call site (the two installers validate
    packages.yaml's `gates:` map, install-system-10-files validates
    system.yaml's `gate:` column, host-facts validates both). A typo is
    therefore still caught at render time, exactly as before — fact_gate()
    only has to PARSE the three grammar shapes at runtime, never police them.
  * CARRY FORCE_* LOGIC. FORCE_NVIDIA / FORCE_INTEL stay in the two package
    installers ONLY, layered on top of fact_gate()'s result:

      HAS_NVIDIA=0; fact_gate "nvidia" && HAS_NVIDIA=1
      [[ "${FORCE_NVIDIA:-0}" == 1 ]] && HAS_NVIDIA=1

    install-system-10-files shares this very partial, and a leaked FORCE_* could
    layer a privilege-granting /etc drop-in onto a host whose fact is false —
    see the FORCE_* note at the bottom of .chezmoidata/facts.yaml.

The dispatch table inside fact_gate() is rendered FROM the fact registry
(.factRegistry), one `case` arm per declared fact mapping its name to the
FACT_<NAME> variable facts-sh.tmpl assigned it (the SAME `snakecase | upper`
formula, so the two can never name-drift apart) — so every valid fact gets an
arm BY CONSTRUCTION, and the `*)` arm below is unreachable in practice. It
aborts loudly anyway: an unmatched bash `case` silently falls through with
exit status 0 (true), and for a gate that GRANTS a package group or an /etc
file, a silent true is a silent GRANT of the one thing this whole registry
exists to make impossible — the same footgun install-system-10-files' own
gate_ok() has warned about since it was written.
*/ -}}
{{- $registry := .factRegistry -}}
{{- $lines := list -}}
{{- range $name := (keys $registry | sortAlpha) -}}
{{-   $var := printf "FACT_%s" ($name | snakecase | upper) -}}
{{-   $lines = append $lines (printf "    %s) value=\"$%s\" ;;" $name $var) -}}
{{- end -}}
# fact_gate — evaluate a gate expression (KTD6: <fact> | !<fact> | <fact>.<value>)
# against the FACT_* variables facts-sh.tmpl assigned above. Returns 0 when the
# gate holds, 1 when it does not; an empty expression is ungated (always 0).
fact_gate() {
  local expr="$1" negate=0 name value want
  [[ -z "$expr" ]] && return 0
  if [[ "$expr" == '!'* ]]; then
    negate=1
    expr="${expr#!}"
  fi
  if [[ "$expr" == *.* ]]; then
    name="${expr%%.*}"
    want="${expr#*.}"
  else
    name="$expr"
    # facts-sh.tmpl renders a true boolean as 1, not the word "true".
    want=1
  fi
  case "$name" in
{{ join "\n" $lines }}
    *)
      # Unreachable by construction (see the header) — every registry fact has
      # an arm above. Guarded anyway: an unmatched `case` falls through with
      # exit status 0, which here would mean silently GRANTING the gate.
      printf 'fact_gate: unknown fact "%s" reached fact_gate() — facts-validate.tmpl should have aborted the render before this ran; aborting.\n' "$name" >&2
      exit 1
      ;;
  esac
  if [[ "$value" == "$want" ]]; then
    return "$negate"
  fi
  return $((1 - negate))
}
